{
  "title": "Docker Based Livecode Server",
  "story": [
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "7cf53f1eff8e1076",
      "text": "Here we explore how we might run a Livecode server using Docker."
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "229576edd676d846",
      "text": "# Aims"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "fd4ee6d1d438306c",
      "text": "The aim is to be able to integrate Livecode scripting into a scaleable cluster based architecture, which will allow easy scripting of automation tasks, and development of server based code for mobile apps."
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "cfb731e2827cbc57",
      "text": "There are two versions of this set up:\n\n- [[Caddy Based Federation]]\n- [[Cluster Based Federation]]\n- [[Docker Data Volumes]]"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "c418791cc44cb94d",
      "text": "# Basic Docker Setup"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "be3a93a1e3523d92",
      "text": "Here is a a Docker image with Apache + LiveCode Community Server installed to the Docker Hub registry - [https://registry.hub.docker.com/u/techstrategies/livecode/ registry.hub.docker.com]"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "2a41ca1e7696e2f9",
      "text": "Here is the repo on [https://github.com/techstrategies/docker-livecode github]"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "6937afba30f6bcf3",
      "text": " To use, simply run the following command from the directory where you have your LiveCode scripts:"
    },
    {
      "type": "code",
      "id": "d7d7d74dbda31275",
      "text": "docker run -it --rm -P --name livecode -v \"$PWD\":/var/www/html/ techstrategies/livecode:7.0.6"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "566c522e46884f0b",
      "text": "Now let's try this on [[Containership.io]]"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "2d545f18bead440c",
      "text": "# Livecode Server on Docker"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "ebb70561699386dc",
      "text": "Setting up a Docker image is fairly simple.  I am guessing you are wanting to run a LiveCode Linux standalone in a Docker container that listens on a particular port?"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "e153cc2773a77599",
      "text": "In that case, it would be a matter of configuring a Dockerfile that uses a base Docker image for whatever distro you prefer, copies the standalone into it, and sets it to execute on startup of the container…  "
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "2704c58b3a97e93c",
      "text": "For what you are doing the Dockerfile might look something like:"
    },
    {
      "type": "code",
      "id": "a8549de21727e039",
      "text": "FROM: ubuntu:14.04\n\nEXPOSE 5000 (put what port you are using here)\n\nCOPY yourstandalone /linux/path/to/yourstandalone\n\nENTRYPOINT [“/linux/path/to/yourstandalone”]\nCMD [“-p parameter”, “-y another parameter”]"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "f6912661d9c92557",
      "text": "Then, making sure that the Dockerfile and standalone are in the current directory, build it…. \"docker build -t image name .\"\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "html",
      "id": "de13115c0f6a22e2",
